      "source": "Surveys/questionnaires administered pre-weekend (Friday), post-weekend (Sunday), and at the end of the following workweek (Friday)",
      "wave_or_subset": "Three measurement points: Time 1 (Friday before weekend), Time 2 (Sunday after weekend), Time 3 (following Friday)",
      "sample_size": "229",
      "unit_of_analysis": "Individual (preschool teacher)",
      "access_details": "not stated",
      "notes": "Participants were 229 preschool teachers in Germany (97.4% female; mean age 38.19 years; mean job experience 15.12 years). Measures included the Recovery Experience Questionnaire (relaxation, mastery, control, psychological detachment) and an extended PANAS-X for discrete affective states (joviality, serenity, self-assurance; hostility, fear, sadness, fatigue) on a 5-point Likert scale. Reliability (Cronbach\u2019s alpha) ranged from 0.70 to 0.94. Longitudinal design with controls for baseline affective states and demographics."
    },
    "method": {
      "description": "A longitudinal survey study of preschool teachers examined how weekend recovery experiences (relaxation, mastery, control, detachment) and non-work hassles relate to discrete affective states at the end of the weekend and during the following workweek. Recovery experiences and affect were measured at three time points. Confirmatory factor analyses evaluated the distinctiveness of affective states, and hierarchical regressions tested relationships controlling for prior affect and demographics.",
      "steps": [
        "Recruit 229 preschool teachers in Germany and collect demographics.",
        "Administer Time 1 (Friday pre-weekend) survey to assess baseline affective states.",
        "Over the weekend, assess recovery experiences (relaxation, mastery, control, psychological detachment) and non-work hassles.",
        "Administer Time 2 (Sunday post-weekend) survey to assess discrete affective states.",
        "Administer Time 3 (following Friday) survey to assess affective states during the subsequent workweek.",
        "Compute reliability (Cronbach\u2019s alpha) for scales.",
        "Conduct confirmatory factor analyses to compare seven-factor vs. two-factor affect models.",
        "Run hierarchical regression analyses predicting Time 2 and Time 3 affective states from weekend recovery experiences and hassles, controlling for demographics and baseline (Time 1) affect.",
        "Interpret coefficients, variance explained (R\u00b2), and significance levels."
      ],
      "models": "Hierarchical regression analyses; Confirmatory Factor Analysis (CFA) comparing seven-factor and two-factor affect models",
      "outcome_variable": "Discrete affective states at Time 2 and Time 3: joviality, serenity, self-assurance (positive); hostility, fear, sadness, fatigue (negative)",
      "independent_variables": "Weekend recovery experiences: relaxation, mastery, control, psychological detachment; non-work hassles during the weekend",
      "control_variables": "Baseline affective states (Time 1); demographic variables (e.g., age, gender), job experience",
      "tools_software": "not stated"
    },
    "results": {
      "summary": "Weekend recovery experiences were related to both positive and negative affective states after the weekend and into the following workweek. Relaxation consistently increased joviality, self-assurance, and serenity and reduced fear and hostility, with effects strongest immediately after the weekend. Mastery was associated with higher positive affect at the end of the weekend but not consistently into the workweek. Psychological detachment enhanced serenity. Non-work hassles increased hostility, fear, sadness, and fatigue. A seven-factor affect model fit the data better than a two-factor model across time points.",
